This is a report presenting the anlaysis of the income gap between females and males. I have used NLSY79 (National Longitudinal Survey of Youth, 1979 cohort) data set for figuring out various factors affecting income gap.

This is a hypothesis testing based analysis.

NULL Hypthesis: There is no income gap between males and females.

The report is split into four section: Data Setup, Data Summary, Methodology, Findings, and Discussion

To start with, below scripts loads, cleanse, and transforms the data.

Data Summary

There are 67 variables present in the data set. Above summary provides mean, median, quartile, etc related statistics for each variable.

A Brief About the Data

Of the 12686 survey respondents, 6283 were females and rest 6403 were males . There are 12 % of BLACK female respondents for 13% males, 8 % of HISPANIC female reposndents for 8 % males. Also, most of the respondents belong to NON-BLACK and NON-HISPNAIC race, this counted for 29 % females and 29 % males.

Out of all the respondents, 93% are born in the US.

61.245434 % of the females are from ‘NONSOUTH’ region and 38.754566% females are from ‘SOUTH’ region. The values are very close to the males proportaions where 61.9634% are from NONSOUTH and 38.0366% are from SOUTH.

In this analysis of the income gap between males and females, the focus will be on below variables:

Factor Variables - race, gender, occupation.2011, region.current.2011
Integer Variables - total.income.2011, family.size.2011, no.drinks.daily, num.job.2011


As said before, there are four factor variables and four integer variables.

  1. Occupation reported in 2011

In the above table, we see the distribution of income by occupation.The color and shape denotes gender of the person reporting the salary. We see in the above diagram that females have mostly reported low salaries for various occupations. In our analysis, we will check whether this difference in incomes drives income gap or not.

  1. Race


In the above figure, we see the distribution of income by race for both the gender. We see in the above diagram that there is income gap between females and males for different races. We see largest income gap in the race Others. In our analysis ahead, we will check whether this difference is statically significant.

  1. Current Region of Stay

In the above figure, we see the distribution of income by region for both the gender. We see in the above diagram that there is income gap between females and males for different regions We see largest income gap in the NORTHCENTRAL and WEST regions. In our analysis ahead, we will check whether this difference is statically significant.

  1. Family Size in 2011

We can see in the above graph that within same family size group, males on average have higher income than females. There is visible gap between the average incomes of females and males. We will test its significane later in the analysis.

  1. Number of Jobs Reported

We can see in the above graph that within same number of jobs changed, males on average have higher income than females. There is visible gap between the average incomes of females and males. We will test its significane later in the analysis.

  1. Alcohol Consumption

We can see in the above graph that within same level of alcohol consumption per day, males on average have higher income than females. There is visible gap between the average incomes of females and males. We will test its significane later in the analysis.

  1. Educational Qualification

We can see in the above graph that within same level of highest education attacined, males on average have higher income than females. There is visible gap between the average incomes of females and males. We will test its significane later in the analysis.

Methodology

  1. How did you deal with missing values? What impact does your approach have on the interpretation or generalizability of the resulting analysis?

I changed all the missing values to ‘NA’ as there were no informative explanation of them present.

We can not map the negative values in the variables to any specific numeric value or certain factor level . Hence, this approch helped me in working with the data records that was better reflective of the respond by the survey respondents.

  1. How did you deal with topcoded variables? What impact does your approach have on the interpretation or generalizability of the resulting analysis?

Income.total.2011 integer vector had top-coded values as shown below in the diagram below.These topcoded values are an average of top 2% of the high income getters. Here, this average value represents both female and male. Because we are focused on analysing the income gap between male and female, this average is not important to us. Hence, I removed all these topcoded values so that analysis is based upon relevant data.

  1. Did you produce any tables or plots that you thought would reveal interesting trends but didn’t?

Yes, as per my analysis (in the figure below), I found that occupation had an income gap between males and females. However, on running the model with interaction term ’occupation.2011*gender’ (in the table below), I found that the coefficients were not that significant. There is only one significant value in that interaction model.

  1. What relationships did you investigate that don’t appear in your findings section?

Yes, as per my analysis (in the figure below), I found that region had an income gap between males and females. However, on running the model with interaction term ’region.current.2011*gender’ (in the table below) , I found that the coefficients were not significant.


  1. What’s the analysis that you finally settled on? What income and gender related factors do you investigate in the final analysis?

Finally, I added highest.grade.2011 variable to the models with the interaction term. Income and gender are getting impacted by race, occupation, and highest degree.

Findings:

In order to find out the factors affecting income gap, we will start with plotting the boxplot and understanding how the average income by gender has changed with time.

Statistical Significance Testing

We will start by comparing the outcome of the two variables income and gender against our chosen variables (race, occupation, number of jobs, drinks consumed, region living in, and family size), the record that we focus is of year 2011. Also, we are using top-coded values.

We can see that the mean income of females is lower than that of males. This plot suggests that gender is associated with income. We can also see outliers incomes in the upper part of box plot in both female and male’s incomes.

##   gender total.income.2011.mean total.income.2011.se
## 1 FEMALE             28492.3221             505.8242
## 2   MALE             41834.0904             675.9342

We can see that the mean income of females is lower than that of males. This plot suggests that gender is associated with income. We can also see outliers incomes in the upper part of box plot in both female and male’s incomes.

Our study finds that income is on average -13341.8g higher in males compared to the females (t-statistic -15.8, p=0, 95% CI [-14996.8, -11686.8] dollars).

Above plot is of kernel density estimate.The density of male and female income is very much overlapping.

The plot above is for income of the females. It is highly right skewed as the right tail starts deviating before quartile point 2. Also, the right tail end is lighter as compared to the center around 0, which denotes non-uniform distribution of data. Hence, the data is highly non-normal.

The plot above is for income of the males. It is highly right skewed as the right tail starts deviating before quartile point 2. We see, the distribustion going away from the normal around ’theoretical quartiles’2, but it agaian comes towards the center line. However, the concentration of the data points decreases. Hence, the data is non-normal.

Both the tail end in the upper diagram deviates from the straight line denoting normalancy. As the data on the above plot doesnot lie on a straight line, we can say that it is not normal.

It looks like there’s some association, but we don’t yet know if it’s statistically significant.This is explained ahead along with graphical plot.

Linear Regression

Interpretation of the Coefficients This model assumes independent effects for all the variables mentioned. In the above table, we have 55 coefficients.

We have 5 factor variables and 3 integers variables in our basic model.For each factor predictor variable, there is one taken for baseline intercept.

From race, ‘Black’ is baseline, from gender - female is baseline, from occupation - ‘Cleaning and Building Service Occupations, from highest grade’ - ‘North Center’1st grade’ is baseline, and region - North Center.

All the factor variables are split into levels to make an individual coefficient. For example, ‘region.current.2011’ factor got split into 4 levels, where the one coming first in the alphabetic order became intercept.

Interpretation of the P-value

In the above table, column ‘Pr(>|t|)’ represents p-value of the predictor variables metioned in the first column. We know that a predictor variable is significant when it has p-value below 0.05.

Looking at p-values in the above table, there are 22 significant values across all variables. Some of the variables are: region.current.2011SOUTH, family.size.2011, num.job.2011, raceOTHERS, and raceHISPANIC.

However, we will have to check the estimate value of these variables as well to know the scale of the impact. Additionally, the sign of the estimate value tells us whether there is a positive association or negative. We have 21 positive associated predictor values, such as no.drinks.daily, genderMALE, highest.2011.grade12TH GRADE, raceHISPANIC, raceOTHERS.

There is one negatively associated significant predictor variable, i.e. num.job.2011. There is an example of positive and negative associated predictor variables in the table below:

Description of Diagnostic Plots

Residuals vs. Fitted

There is a indication of non-linearity present in this plot. Furthermore, we see that the variance appears to be increasing across fitted value.

Normal QQ plot

The residuals depart significantly from the diagonal line in both the lower and major part of the upper tail of the distribution. Also, we see a gap where no values are present. This indicates that the residuals are not normally distributed. Interestingly, they appear to be more highly concentrated around 0 than we would expect from the normal (i.e., they have lighter tails than a normal).

Scale-location plot

We see a clear increasing trend in residual variance that runs through most of the plot. This is indicated by the upward slope of the red line, which we can interpret as the standard deviation of the residuals at the given level of fitted value.

Residuals vs Leverage.

None of the points appear to be outliers.

There is no colinearity between the specified variables.

Race turns out to be a highly statistically signficant predictor of income in the model. On comparing our old and new model, we checked that we found that p-value if 0.00000006333 which is <0.05. We can see by looking at the coefficient estimates and standard errors - the estimated coefficients are very large, with relatively small standard errors. Hence, factor variable race is a significant variable.

Interpretation of Coefficients There are two estimated coefficients for this interaction term. These coefficients correspond to differences in earnings across gender and race that aren’t accounted for by a model that assumes independent effects for race and gender (as in nlsy.lm1). That is, the income difference between men and women appears to depend strongly on the individual’s race. For instance, the income difference among mixed-race men and mixed-race women is $9045 more than the difference between black men and black women. Race is a factor that is highly associated with the income gap between men and women.

Interpretation of Output The Estimate for the two coefficients are positively associated with the intercept. Also, looking at the P-value, it can be identified that both the coefficients are highly significant. For instance, all the other factor in the model staying same, the income difference between hispanic men and hispanic women is $4079 more than the difference between black men and black women.

On comparing two models (the one with interaction variable and the one without, we found that the p-value is statistically significant as it is 0.0000003779 (it has to be <0.05). Hence, we can reject the null hypothesis that the income gap is the same across all the race categories. In other words, race is a highly significant factor impacting income, therefore, all other variables kept same, the data suggests that the income gap between men and women does vary with race.

Interpretation of Coefficients

There are 17 estimated coefficients for this interaction term. Interpretation of Output

13 coefficients are positively associated and 4 coefficients are negatively assciated with the intercept which is ‘1st grade’ for this interaction term. Also, looking at the P-value, it can be identified that 15 coefficients are not significant as their p-value is >0.05. Only two coefficients (4th Year College and 5th Year College) is signficant here having p-value 0.02 and 0.03. the income difference among men and women having ‘4th Year College’ education is $12452 more than the difference between men and women having highest degree to 1st grade only. Highest degree is a factor that is slightly associated with the income gap between men and women.

Normal QQ plot

This indicates that the residuals are not normally distributed. Interestingly, they appear to be more highly concentrated around 0 than we would expect from the normal (i.e., they have lighter tails than a normal).

Scale-location plot

We see a clear increasing trend in residual variance that runs through most of the plot. This is indicated by the upward slope of the red line, which we can interpret as the standard deviation of the residuals at the given level of fitted value.

Residuals vs Leverage.

None of the points appear to be outliers.

Discussion

Summary of the main conclusions

After my analysis and findings, I can say that income gap is highly affected by race. Other factors such as occupation and highest grade studied does impact the income gap but slightly. I did not see much significant predictor variables while modeling on interaction terms. Though simple model shows that all these variables are highly significant but that information is not a true reflective of the income gap, however, it does show us about difference in income along various variables.

Non-factor variables such as family size and number of jobs changed also reflect on income gap.

In our conclusion, I can say that, income gap is more or little affected by race, gender, highest grade, occupation. family size, and number of jobs changed by a person.

Potential limitations of analysis and findings

A imitation of the analysis is that it is focused on few variables, that too preferably latest one. There is no trend analysis done in it. There was no analysis done to map highest grade and occupation against income and gender to check how in combination they impact salary gap.

Another limitation of the analysis is that it doesnot include any experience information. There may be a case that our sample has women with less number of experience and men with more experience. Hence, the analysis has its limitation of not going in depth categories to provide a comprehensive outcome.

The findings is also based on few latest variables in the model. It doesnot give the holistic picture of the scenario.
